########################################################
###################### OVERVIEW ########################
########################################################
## Xenoseq is pipeline of (meta)genomic tools to extract
## contigs that are unique to a dataset. To use it, you
## have to submit a query file (in which it will look for 
## unique contigs), one or more subject files (which will
## be used as a reference for which sequences are unique)
## in fasta format. If you have uncorrected fastq files,
## you either have to quality trim them yourself, or use
## the xenoseq_prep command to use our methods of prep. 

########################################################
####################### INSTALL ########################
########################################################
## To use xenoseq, a conda environment is provided. (see
## https://docs.conda.io/projects/conda/en/latest/) To
## install your conda environment, simply use: 'conda env
## create -f conda_env.yml'. If you prefer using other 
virtual environments, this yml-file will provide you with
all the required packages and their version. 

########################################################
####################### TESTRUN ########################
########################################################
## To test whether everything is working, try using the 
## example program './xenoseq_example', which will use
## mock reads found in samples/reads and will search for
## (artficially added) unique contigs. Your unique contigs
## will be in the file "xenoseq_contigs.fasta".
##########################################################

